{{lang|la|'''Disjecta membra'''}}, also written {{lang|la|disiecta membra}}, is [[Latin language|Latin]] for "scattered fragments" (also scattered limbs, members, or remains) and is used to refer to surviving fragments of ancient poetry, manuscripts, and other literary or cultural objects, including even fragments of ancient pottery.  It is derived from {{lang|la|disiecti membra poetae}}, a phrase used by [[Horace]], a [[Roman poetry|Roman poet]].<ref>Oxford English Dictionary.</ref>

==Ancient and medieval poetry, literature, and manuscripts==

[[File:DSC00276 - Processione di donne - 570-550 a.C. - Foto G. Dall'Orto.jpg|thumb|250px|{{lang|la|Disjecta membra}} (a fragment of [[Pottery of ancient Greece|ancient Greek pottery]])]]
Fragments of ancient writing, especially ancient [[Latin poetry]] found in other works are commonly referred to as ''disjecta membra''.<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/disjecta+membra Dictionary.com]</ref> The terms ''disiecta membra'' and ''disjecta membra'' are paraphrased from the Roman [[Lyric poetry|lyric poet]] [[Horace]] (65 BC  – 8 BC), who wrote of {{lang|la|disiecti membra poetae}} in his [[Satires (Horace)|''Satires'']], 1.4.62, referring to the "limbs of a dismembered poet".<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=disjecta+membra Online Etymology Dictionary]. See also [[List of Latin phrases (D)]]</ref>  In full, the term originally appeared as {{lang|la|Invenias etiam disiecti membra poetae}}, in reference to the earlier Roman poet [[Ennius]].<ref>Horace, {{lang|la|Sermonum Liber Primus}} (Satires), 1.4.62.</ref>

Although Horace's intended meaning remains the subject of speculation and debate, the passage is often taken to imply that if a line from poetry were torn apart and rearranged, the dismembered parts of the poet would still be recognisable.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}} In this sense, in the study of [[literature]], ''disjecta membra'' is often used to describe the piecing together of ancient fragments of an identifiable literary source. Similarly, isolated leaves or parts of leaves from ancient or medieval manuscripts may also be termed ''disjecta membra''.  Scholars have been able to identify [[fragmentology (manuscripts)|fragments]] now held in different libraries that originally belonged to the same manuscript.  <ref>See, e.g., Babcock, Robert Gary; Davis, Lisa Fagin & Rusche, Philip G., Catalogue Of Medieval And Renaissance Manuscripts In The Beinecke Rare Book And Manuscript Library At Yale University: MSS 184 - 485 (Medieval and Renaissance Texts and Studies: V. 34, 48, 100, 176), Brepols Pub. (2004), p. xviii {{ISBN|978-2503514406}}.</ref>

==Pottery==

Scholars have long referred to [[sherd]]s of [[Pottery of ancient Greece|ancient Greek pottery]] as {{lang|la|disjecta membra}}.  They have studied fragments of ancient Greek pottery in institutional collections, and have attributed many such pieces to the artists who made them.  In a number of instances, they have been able to identify fragments now in different collections that belong to the same vase.<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=4301546|title=Fragments of Antiquity: Drawing upon Greek Vases|first=Aaron J.|last=Paul|date=January 1, 1997|publisher=|journal=Harvard University Art Museums Bulletin|volume=5|issue=2|pages=4 & 10|issn=1065-6448}}</ref>

