'''Abū–l-Walīd ‛Abdallāh ibn ul-Faradi''' (962{{snd}}1012), best known as '''Ibn Faradi''', was a [[Muladi]] [[historian]]. He was born at [[Córdoba, Spain|Córdoba]] and studied law and tradition. In 992, he made the [[pilgrimage]] and proceeded to [[Egypt]] and [[Kairawan]], studying in these places. After his return, in 1009 he became [[qadi]] in [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]]. He and his fellow [[Muladi]]s were killed at Córdoba when the [[Berber people|Berbers]] took the city.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Ibn Faradī |volume=14 |page=220 |inline=1 |first=Griffithes Wheeler |last=Thatcher}}</ref>
Ibn Faradi's chief work is the ''History of the Learned Men of Andalusia'', edited by F. Codera ([[Madrid]], 1891{{snd}}1892). He also wrote a history of the poets of [[Andalusia]].<ref name=EB1911/>
