{{Infobox philosopher | region = Islamic scholar | era = Medieval era | color = #B0C4DE | name = Muhammad Khwandamir | birth_date = c. 1475 | birth_place = Herat, [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] (now in Afghanistan) <ref name=britannica/> | death_date = 1534/37 | death_place = buried in Delhi, India <ref name=britannica/> | school_tradition = | main_interests = | influences = | influenced = | notable_ideas = }}
'''Ghiyāś ad-Dīn Muḥammad Khwāndamīr''', '''Khvandamir''', or '''Khondamir''' or '''Hondemir''' ({{lang-fa|غياث الدين محمد خواندامير}}) (1475–1534) was a [[Persian people|Persian]]<ref name="Donzel1994">{{cite book|last1=Donzel|first1=E. J. van|title=Islamic Desk Reference|date=1 January 1994|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-09738-4|page=212|quote=Khwandamir: surname of the Persian historian Ghiyath al-Din; ca. 1475ca. 1535. His most valuable work is a general history from the earliest times down to the end of the reign of Shah Ismail.}}</ref> [[Islamic scholar]]<ref name=britannica>[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9045363/Ghiyas-ad-Din-Muhammad-Khwandamir#25246.hook Ghiyas ad-Din Muhammad Khwandamir - Britannica Online Encyclopedia]</ref> born in [[Herat]], in 880 AH or 1475 CE,<ref>{{cite book|last=Elliot|first=H. M. (Henry Miers), Sir|author2=John Dowson|title=[[The History of India, as Told by Its Own Historians. The Muhammadan Period]] (Vol 4.)|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924073036745#page/n3/mode/2up|year=1871|chapter=24. Khulásatu-l Akhbár, of Khondamir|publisher=London: Trübner & Co.|page=141}}.</ref> a grandson and successor to noted historian [[Mirkhond]].
==Biography== Hondamir, like his grandfather, belonged to the Herat literary circle of [[Timurid dynasty|Timurid]] vizier [[Ali-Shir Nava'i|Mir Ali-Shir Navai]]. In 1527 the [[Mughal Empire|Moghul]] conqueror [[Babur]] invited Hondamir to India, where he lived and died. Hondamir edited and completed 7th and 8th volums of the general history composed by his grandfather, and approximately in 1500 composed an extract from it "Holaset el-ehbar".<ref>Price D., ''Memoirs of the Principal Events of Mahommedan History'', London, 1821, reprint General Books, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-154-13938-9}}, (''partial English translation'') </ref> Following the same pattern, in 1521 Hondamir composed for Ali-Shir Navai a three-volume general history entitled "[[Habib al-Siyar]]", and brought it to his time.<ref>Grigoriev, ''History of the Mongols from ancientest Times to Tamerlane, Composition by Hondemir'', St. Petersburg, 1849 (''translation'')</ref> Another notable work was "Al-Destour Voser".<ref>Elliot, ''History of India'', IV, 148-153</ref> In the European languages, other works of Hondemir were not published.
==Works== * [[Habib al-Siyar]] *{{cite book|last=Elliot|first=H. M. (Henry Miers), Sir|author2=John Dowson|title=[[The History of India, as Told by Its Own Historians. The Muhammadan Period]] (Vol 4.)|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924073036745#page/n3/mode/2up|year=1871|chapter=24. Khulásatu-l Akhbár, of Khondamir|publisher=London : Trübner & Co.}} *{{cite book|last=Elliot|first=H. M. (Henry Miers), Sir|author2=John Dowson|title=[[The History of India, as Told by Its Own Historians. The Muhammadan Period]] (Vol 4.)|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924073036745#page/n161/mode/2up|year=1871|chapter=25. Dastúru-l Wuzrá, of Khondamír|publisher=London : Trübner & Co.}} *{{cite book|last=Elliot|first=H. M. (Henry Miers), Sir|author2=John Dowson|title=[[The History of India, as Told by Its Own Historians. The Muhammadan Period]] (Vol 4.)|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924073036745#page/n167/mode/2up|year=1871|chapter=26. Habib al-Siyar, of Khondamír|publisher=London : Trübner & Co.}}
