{{Infobox writer | name = Stefan Maechler | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|yy|mm|dd}} --> | birth_place = | occupation = Historian, author | genre = | movement = | notableworks = ''Der Fall Wilkomirski'' | influences = | influenced = | website = }} '''Stefan Maechler''' is a [[Swiss]] historian and expert on anti-Semitism and [[Switzerland]]'s treatment of Holocaust refugees during and after [[World War II]]. Maechler studied history and [[German literature]] at the [[University of Zurich]]. He was commissioned by the [[Schocken Books]] specializing in [[Judaica]] to conduct a full-scale investigation into the life of writer [[Binjamin Wilkomirski]] whose memoir ''Fragments'', published by Schocken in 1996, sparked international controversy.<ref name="books.google">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4oly8ZeSgIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Wilkomirski Affair: A Study in Biographical Truth | publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group | work=Biography | date=2009 | accessdate=21 March 2015 | author=Stefan Maechler | format=Google Books, preview}}</ref> Maechler studied hundreds of personal documents, and has interviewed eyewitnesses and families of survivors in seven countries. He was given unrestricted access to government files, and subsequently, discovered facts that completely refuted Wilkomirski's bestselling book as a [[forgery]].<ref name="observer"/> Maechler published his findings in a book called ''The Wilkomirski Affair: A Study in Biographical Truth'' by Schocken Books, New York, in 2001 (496 pp.); originally in the German language as ''Der Fall Wilkomirski: über die Wahrheit einer Biographie'' by Pendo Verlag AG, Zurich, 2000. Maechler lives and works in [[Zurich]].<ref name="JSTOR">{{cite web | url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/42944065?sid=21105283714861&uid=3737720&uid=3739400&uid=4&uid=70&uid=2&uid=2129 | title=The Wilkomirski Affair: A Study in Biographical Truth by Stefan Maechler | publisher=JSTOR | work=Shofar, Vol. 21, No. 1, Special Issue | date=2002 | accessdate=7 February 2015 | author=Lawrence Birken | pages=174-176}}</ref><ref name="randomhouse">{{cite web | url=http://www.randomhouse.com/book/106002/the-wilkomirski-affair-by-stefan-maechler | title=The Wilkomirski Affair. A Study in Biographical Truth. Written by Stefan Maechler | publisher=Penguin Random House | work=About the Book: Synopsis. About the Author | date=2015 | accessdate=7 February 2015 | author=Random House | ISBN=978-0-8052-1135-1 | format=Look Inside}}</ref><ref name="observer">{{cite web | url=http://observer.com/2001/04/a-holocaust-fraud-exposed-a-peccadillo-papered-over/ | title=A Holocaust Fraud Exposed, a Peccadillo Papered Over | publisher=Observer Media | work=Arts and Culture | date=April 30, 2001 | accessdate=7 February 2015 | author=Rick Perlstein | quote=Author of ''Before the Storm: Barry Goldwater and the Unmaking of the American Consensus'' by Hill & Wang.}}</ref>
