{{Infobox UN resolution |number = 363 |organ = SC |date = 29 November |year = 1974 |meeting = 1,809 |code = S/RES/363 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/363(1974) |for = 13 |abstention = 0 |against = 0 |subject = Israel-Syrian Arab Republic |result = Adopted |image = |caption = }}
'''[[United Nations]] [[List of UN Security Council Resolutions|Security Council Resolution]] 363''', adopted on November 29, 1974, after considering a report by the [[United Nations Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] regarding the [[United Nations Disengagement Observer Force Zone|United Nations Disengagement Observer Force]], the Council noted the efforts made to establish a durable and just peace in the [[Middle East]] and expressed its concern over the prevailing state of tension in the area. The Council reaffirmed that the agreements on disengagement of forces were only a step toward peace and called upon all the parties concerned to implement immediately [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 338|resolution 338]], decided to renew the mandate of the Force for another six months and decided that the Secretary-General would submit a report at the end of that period regarding developments in the situation and measures taken to implement resolution 338.
The resolution passed with 13 votes to none, while [[People's Republic of China|China]] and [[Iraq]] did not participate in voting.
